Posted: Mon Oct 28, 2013 9:45 am
arsoofi wrote:Quote:German magazine Der Spiegel published an investigative report noting that US intelligence officials "used the American Embassy in Berlin as a listening station."I wonder how tid-bits like these are going to affect foreign relations.Probably not much. What's going on right now is public discussion of things that were already well known or assumed in private among diplomats. For instance, if there were evidence that appeared showing that the US Embassy in Beijing were spying on Chinese citizens, the Chinese government would have to get really angry and stamp its feet and so on like the Germans are doing now in order to make its citizens happy. But every single day, they already operate on the assumption that the US is spying on them from the Embassy. Or if they don't, they're idiots. Which they're not. I have an equally high opinion of German leaders. This is a show for the public, but the leaders are already well aware of what goes on.What's surprising to the public is apparently the fact that even most "allies" aren't exempt from spying on one another. But I'd encourage people to read a little diplomatic history and consider the nature of international relations before concluding that this is a major aberration.
